description:
Cygnus is so rich in striking targets whether narrowband or tradition broadband and here I have eschewed any restraint and allowed the rich narrowband possibilities to display the swirling molecular dust and structures in the gases to their unabashed glory.  The ridge-like VdB130 contrasts with the swirling dark cloud of B344 with its globules and fluted manifold structure - a mysterious delight.

It's also been rewarding to capture an image from my home observatory to which I've had to give it a 'birthday' with strengthening my western wall which had warped slightly over the years and had caused a minor slew to my roof's rail; and also a leak on the windward side that took some ingenuity to plug.

Let me know if the image is too bright ;-) & thanks for looking.
imaging_telescopes: William Optics FLT 132 Triplet APO f/7
title: Van den Bergh 130 and Barnard 344
